<p><i><b>Snow Crash</b></i> is <a href="/wiki/Neal_Stephenson" title="Neal Stephenson">Neal Stephenson</a>'s third <a href="/wiki/Novel" title="Novel">novel</a>, published in 1992. Like many of Stephenson's other novels it references <a href="/wiki/History" title="History">history</a>, <a href="/wiki/Linguistics" title="Linguistics">linguistics</a>, <a href="/wiki/Anthropology" title="Anthropology">anthropology</a>, <a href="/wiki/Archaeology" title="Archaeology">archaeology</a>, <a href="/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religion</a>, <a href="/wiki/Computer_science" title="Computer science">computer science</a>, <a href="/wiki/Politics" title="Politics">politics</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cryptography" title="Cryptography">cryptography</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophy</a>.</p>
<p>Stephenson explained the title of the novel in his 1999 essay <i><a href="/wiki/In_the_Beginning...was_the_Command_Line" title="In the Beginning...was the Command Line" class="mw-redirect">In the Beginning...was the Command Line</a></i> as his term for a particular software <a href="/wiki/Failure_mode" title="Failure mode" class="mw-redirect">failure mode</a> on the early <a href="/wiki/Apple_Macintosh" title="Apple Macintosh" class="mw-redirect">Apple Macintosh</a> computer. Stephenson wrote about the Macintosh that "when the computer crashed and wrote gibberish into the bitmap, the result was something that looked vaguely like <a href="/wiki/Noise_(video)" title="Noise (video)">static on a broken television</a> set — a 'snow crash'".</p>
